// @test: run-interpreter
// @tier: 0
// @level: L0
// @tags: memory-safety, null-safety, raw-pointer, method-dispatch, regression
// @timeout: 5000
// @expected-stdout: ok
// @expected-exit: 0
// @description: Regression guardrail for #201.
//
// Pins the codegen-level fix that routes `is_null()` on raw-pointer
// receivers (`&unsafe T`, `*const T`, `*mut T`) directly to the
// `ptr_is_null` intrinsic instead of CallM-dispatching by bare name.
//
// Pre-fix: codegen emitted `CallM` keyed by the bare name `is_null`.
// The runtime resolved that to the user-defined `FatRef.is_null`
// function (registered when `core/mem/fat_ref.vr` was processed),
// which reads `self.generation` at offset 0.  A raw pointer has no
// generation field, so its u64 address was reinterpreted as a
// generation counter and the runtime panicked with a null-pointer
// dereference at pc=0 inside `FatRef.is_null` — the entire
// `List.try_with_capacity` / `List.with_capacity` allocator surface
// was therefore non-functional.
//
// Fix: `compile_cast` now marks the result register of any cast to
// `&unsafe T` / `*const T` / `*mut T` as a raw pointer, the flag
// propagates through `compile_pattern_bind`'s Mov, and
// `compile_method_call` intercepts `is_null` on raw-pointer
// receivers and emits `Instruction::Call` to the registered
// stdlib-intrinsic function `is_null` (mapped to `ptr_is_null`
// at codegen/mod.rs:1656).
//
// This test exercises the fix end-to-end: a successful
// `List.try_with_capacity(8)` call must reach the `Ok(...)` branch
// of `ptr.is_null()`, NOT panic at FatRef.is_null pc=0.

fn main() {
    let r: Result<List<Int>, AllocError> = List.try_with_capacity(8);
    match r {
        Ok(_) => print("ok"),
        Err(_) => print("err"),
    }
}
